			<A HREF="index.html">Writing UNIX Manual Pages</A> &#8211; <Q>Getting Started</Q>
		</DIV>
		<DIV>
			<H1>SYNOPSIS</H1>
			<P>
				This tutorial illustrates how to prepare an environment for writing portable UNIX manual pages.
			</P>
		</DIV>
		<DIV>
			<H1>DESCRIPTION</H1>
			<P>
				It's quite easy, but may be slightly complicated if your system doesn't have <A CLASS="man external"
				HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mandoc.1.html">mandoc</A> installed.
			</P>
			<OL>
				<LI>
					<P>
						Make sure <A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mandoc.1.html">mandoc</A> exists on
						your system.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% man 1 mandoc
					</P>
					<P>
						If it does not and you don't have the resources to install it, then skip previewing your work in
						<A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mandoc.1.html">mandoc</A> and instead fall
						back to nroff, which will almost certainly be installed.
				</LI>
				<LI>
					<P>
						Copy the manual page template file into your working directory.  We assume that the template is
						installed in <SPAN CLASS="path">/usr/share/misc/</SPAN>.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% cp /usr/share/misc/mdoc.template .
					</P>
					<P>
						If this document is not available on your system, it may be fetched online from 
						<A CLASS="external"
						HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/cgi-bin/cvsweb/~checkout~/mdoc.template?rev=HEAD&amp;cvsroot=mdocml">mdoc.template</A>.
					</P>
				</LI>
				<LI>
					<P>
						Open the <A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html">mdoc</A> language
						reference in another terminal window.  Use the linked, on-line version if this is not available
						on your system.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% man 7 mdoc
					</P>
				</LI>
				<LI>
					<P>
						Rename the template as your command, utility, or device (any reasonable name will do) with a
						suffix corresponding to an available <A CLASS="external"
						HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html#x5c264474">manual section</A>.  In this example, let the
						name be <Q>foo</Q> and the section be <Q>1</Q>, for general utilities.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% mv mdoc.template foo.1
					</P>
				</LI>
				<LI>
					<P>
						Edit the template using the <A CLASS="man external"
						HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html">mdoc</A> reference as a guide.  Preview your work from
						time to time in both terminal and HTML modes.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% mandoc -Wall -fstrict foo.1 |less
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% mandoc -Wall -fstrict -Thtml foo.1 &gt;foo.1.html
					</P>
				</LI>
				<LI>
					<P>
						If <A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mandoc.1.html">mandoc</A> is not
						installed, fall back to using nroff.  You may want to do this to verify the portability of your
						manual anyway.
					</P>
					<P CLASS="code">
						% nroff -Tascii -mandoc foo.1 |less
					</P>
					<P>
						If you're only using nroff to verify your manual, be quite careful that your manual closely
						follows the <A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html">mdoc</A> language
						reference.
					</P>
				</LI>
			</OL>
